A '''marginal seat''' or '''swing seat''' is a [[constituency]] held with a small majority in a [[Legislature|legislative]] [[election]], generally one conducted under a [[single-winner voting system]]. In Canada, they may be known as [[Target ridings in the Canadian federal election, 2006|target ridings]]. The opposite is a [[safe seat]].
These seats only require a small [[Swing (politics)|swing]] to change hands and therefore are typically the focus of most [[Political campaign|campaign]] resources. The concentration of money and manpower in areas where they will make the most difference is known as [[Targeting (politics)|targeting]].
== Strategies for securing swing seats == The creation of policy that will benefit a particular seat, at the expense of other [[taxpayer]]s, is known as [[pork barrel]]ing. <ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2007/11/16/1194766968042.html SMH: Vaile in last-ditch pork barrel]</ref>
Political parties often face tension between the holders of marginal seats and [[safe seat]]s. Safe seats tend to be allocated far less discretionary resources&mdash;governmental as well as political&mdash;from their political party than do marginal seats.
A similar phenomenon happens in [[United States presidential election]]s, where the [[Electoral College (United States)|Electoral College]] system means that candidates must win states rather than votes. Again, resources are concentrated towards the [[swing state]]s with the smallest majorities.
